1
00:00:39,065 --> 00:00:43,857
Mummy got sick.
It happened just like that.

2
00:00:44,904 --> 00:00:48,238
Nobody could stop it.

3
00:00:48,408 --> 00:00:52,192
It isn't fair.
There's no reason.

4
00:00:52,370 --> 00:00:58,076
And if we start asking why,
we'll go crazy.

5
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:25,351
Five minutes in the microwave.
Any one of them.

6
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:30,649
Do you know how to make juice?

7
00:01:33,161 --> 00:01:37,159
Microwave. Five minutes.

8
00:01:52,972 --> 00:01:57,468
Here. It's my shrink.
Call him.

9
00:02:06,527 --> 00:02:10,691
Loss of Spouse Support Group.

10
00:02:10,865 --> 00:02:16,322
Chicago Cancer Family Network.
Parents without Partners.

11
00:02:16,496 --> 00:02:20,873
"Hug Yourself",
"Hug a Friend", "Hug a Shrink" ...

12
00:02:21,042 --> 00:02:26,961
Work hard, that'll save you.
Only work will see you through this.

13
00:02:32,011 --> 00:02:37,219
Don't mind him.
he's just a guy who's lost his wife.

14
00:02:41,312 --> 00:02:45,559
What I think we really need is ...
change.

15
00:02:45,733 --> 00:02:51,154
Good idea. Take a few weeks off.
take Jonah fishing.

16
00:02:52,949 --> 00:02:57,362
No, real change.
A new city.

17
00:02:58,413 --> 00:03:03,454
Some place where I don't think
of Maggie at every corner.

18
00:03:11,175 --> 00:03:14,591
Where are you gonna go?

19
00:03:16,723 --> 00:03:19,807
I was thinking about Seattle.

20
00:03:20,643 --> 00:03:25,638
In a few months, you'll be seeing
women. You'll meet someone.

21
00:03:25,815 --> 00:03:32,945
Move on. fine. that's what I'll do.
I'll just grow a new heart.

22
00:03:33,114 --> 00:03:39,034
- Sam, I'm sorry, I didn't mean ...
- I know. But it can't happen twice.

23
00:05:28,646 --> 00:05:33,771
- The tall redhead is cousin Irene.
- You'll see her disappointed look.

24
00:05:33,943 --> 00:05:40,741
- Harold ran off with the secretary.
- Until Irene had the dog put down.

25
00:05:40,909 --> 00:05:45,736
Your brother Dennis
is professor at Johns Hopkins.

26
00:05:45,914 --> 00:05:51,537
- He's married to ... Betsy.
- The most competitive woman ever.

27
00:05:51,711 --> 00:05:56,207
- How will I remember all this?
- Walter, you will!

28
00:06:08,311 --> 00:06:12,807
- Uncle Milton lost all his money.
- And some other people's.

29
00:06:12,982 --> 00:06:17,561
... in a pyramid scheme. Don't
mention the IRS or the prisons.

30
00:06:17,737 --> 00:06:21,106
Your mother's Barbara.
your father's Cliff ...

31
00:06:21,282 --> 00:06:25,150
- He has electric trains.
- Really?

32
00:06:25,328 --> 00:06:32,659
- Am I what they had in mind?
- Walter, they're gonna love you!

33
00:06:35,171 --> 00:06:40,248
Everybody ...
Annie has an announcement.

34
00:06:40,426 --> 00:06:44,175
Walter and I are engaged.

35
00:07:02,073 --> 00:07:04,196
Bless you!

36
00:07:05,827 --> 00:07:10,868
- Are you all right?
- Maybe it's the flowers.

37
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:15,370
- We'll move them.
- No! I feel terrible, sneezing now.

38
00:07:15,545 --> 00:07:20,622
- This is a very important moment.
- He's just allergic to everything.

39
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:24,299
Bees.
I'm allergic to bees.

40
00:07:24,470 --> 00:07:30,224
He's allergic to all bees. We
have to take adrenalin with us.

41
00:07:30,393 --> 00:07:36,846
- If he eats just a bit of a nut ...
- My head swells, and I drop dead.

42
00:07:37,025 --> 00:07:41,236
- It's the same with him and bees.
- We had salmon at our wedding ...

43
00:07:41,404 --> 00:07:47,193
- A wedding without salmon is ...
- I'm not allergic to salmon.

44
00:07:47,368 --> 00:07:49,859
But you never know.

45
00:07:50,038 --> 00:07:54,166
- You never know.
- He wasn't always allergic to bees.

46
00:07:54,334 --> 00:08:01,629
- What did we do with our champagne?
- Uncle Milton's parole.

47
00:08:01,799 --> 00:08:07,042
- When are you getting married?
- Early June, in the garden.

48
00:08:07,222 --> 00:08:14,220
- What about Harold and bees?
- I'm allergic to bees.

49
00:08:14,395 --> 00:08:18,096
Cold salmon. cucumber salad.
strawberries ...

50
00:08:18,274 --> 00:08:23,435
I'm afraid I am allergic
to strawberries.

51
00:08:24,614 --> 00:08:27,734
Is this all right with you?

52
00:08:27,909 --> 00:08:33,745
I'm the luckiest man-man-man on
the face of the earth-earth-earth.

53
00:08:33,915 --> 00:08:39,953
- That's Lou Gehrig's line from ...
- "Pride of the Yankees".

54
00:08:40,129 --> 00:08:44,875
- "Pride of the Yankees"!
- Baseball. An historical reference.

55
00:08:45,051 --> 00:08:49,796
I would like to propose a toast.
To my kid sister!

56
00:08:49,973 --> 00:08:53,922
To Walter and my baby.

57
00:08:57,313 --> 00:09:01,145
Please eat, before it gets cold.

58
00:09:03,736 --> 00:09:09,691
Here it is. I wouldn't
give it to the Historical Society.

59
00:09:09,867 --> 00:09:14,613
- Oh. Mum ...
- These things are back in fashion.

60
00:09:14,789 --> 00:09:17,956
Grandmother's dress.

61
00:09:19,127 --> 00:09:25,082
- He's a lovely man, Annie.
- He is. isn't he?

62
00:09:25,341 --> 00:09:31,925
And he's a wonderful athlete. We're
going to DC to see his parents.

63
00:09:32,098 --> 00:09:36,226
- How did it happen?
- It's silly, really.

64
00:09:36,394 --> 00:09:41,554
I'd seen him at the office.
He's the associate publisher.

65
00:09:41,733 --> 00:09:45,398
We had both ordered sandwiches. -

66
00:09:45,570 --> 00:09:49,733
- and he got my tomato on wheat,
which he's allergic to, -

67
00:09:49,908 --> 00:09:54,368
- and I got his tomato on white.
Amazing, isn't it?

68
00:09:54,537 --> 00:09:59,532
You make a million decisions.
and a sandwich changes your life.

69
00:09:59,709 --> 00:10:02,461
Destiny takes a hand.

70
00:10:02,629 --> 00:10:08,334
We invented destiny, because we
don't want things to be accidental.

71
00:10:08,509 --> 00:10:13,634
Then why did you order the same
sandwich except for the bread?

72
00:10:13,806 --> 00:10:20,770
How many people like tomato
without something else, like tuna?

73
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:24,848
It wasn't a sign.
It was a coincidence.

74
00:10:25,026 --> 00:10:29,320
I was in Atlantic City,
where Cliff was a waiter.

75
00:10:29,489 --> 00:10:33,949
He wasn't supposed to work
that night. What if he hadn't?

76
00:10:34,118 --> 00:10:41,948
He asked me to take a midnight walk.
I told you this a million times.

77
00:10:42,126 --> 00:10:50,336
He held my hand. I looked down
and couldn't tell our fingers apart.

78
00:10:50,510 --> 00:10:55,088
- And I knew.
- What?

79
00:10:56,808 --> 00:11:02,431
- What?
- It was magic.

80
00:11:04,524 --> 00:11:11,654
I knew we'd be together forever.
Just like you and Walter.

81
00:11:11,823 --> 00:11:16,200
Walter ... It's quite a formal name.

82
00:11:16,953 --> 00:11:23,122
I knew that your father and I would
have a wonderful time in the ...

83
00:11:23,293 --> 00:11:26,792
... sack, I believe you call it.

84
00:11:26,963 --> 00:11:33,250
It took years before it worked
like clockwork. It takes time.

85
00:11:33,428 --> 00:11:38,553
- We already ...
- Fine, fine. How's it working?

86
00:11:38,725 --> 00:11:43,766
- Like clockwork.
- Oh, honey ...

87
00:11:46,065 --> 00:11:50,858
- It's a sign.
- You don't believe in signs.

88
00:11:55,658 --> 00:11:59,952
They loved you.
I told you they would.

89
00:12:00,121 --> 00:12:03,490
- I love you.
- I love you, Walter.

90
00:12:05,335 --> 00:12:10,577
Did anyone ever call you
anything other than Walter?

91
00:12:10,757 --> 00:12:17,127
- Not even when you were young?
- Not even when I was young.

92
00:12:17,305 --> 00:12:22,014
- Don't you want to drive with me?
- Then I can't get back on Friday.

93
00:12:22,185 --> 00:12:28,104
I forgot your stepmother's present.
When we're old and grey -

94
00:12:28,274 --> 00:12:34,478
- you must remind me to put my teeth
in, so I don't go out without them.

95
00:12:34,656 --> 00:12:37,573
I'll wait.

96
00:12:37,742 --> 00:12:43,033
No, go ahead. We're late anyway.
I'll be ten minutes behind you.

97
00:13:13,528 --> 00:13:16,363
Welcome to "You and Emotions".

98
00:13:16,531 --> 00:13:22,237
I'm Dr. Marcia Fieldstone,
broadcasting live from Chicago.

99
00:13:22,412 --> 00:13:28,248
Tonight we'll talk about wishes.
What's your wish this Christmas?

100
00:13:28,418 --> 00:13:33,127
My wish is to change the station.

101
00:13:33,298 --> 00:13:38,540
- And now: "You and your spleen".
- Not on your life.

102
00:13:38,720 --> 00:13:43,465
Coming up, "'Jingle bells" backwards ,
sung by ...

103
00:13:43,641 --> 00:13:47,805
- Seattle, go ahead.
- This is 'Jonah ...

104
00:13:47,979 --> 00:13:52,688
No last names, 'Jonah.
How old are you?

105
00:13:52,859 --> 00:13:55,895
- I'm eight.
- You're up late.

106
00:13:56,070 --> 00:14:01,776
- It's not so late in Seattle.
- You're right. What's your wish?

107
00:14:01,951 --> 00:14:07,621
- My dad needs a new wife.
- You don't like the one he has?

108
00:14:07,790 --> 00:14:11,788
- He doesn't have one.
- Where's your mum?

109
00:14:11,961 --> 00:14:17,632
- She died.
- Well. who can believe this?

110
00:14:17,800 --> 00:14:23,590
- I've been sad, but Dad's worse.
- Have you talked to him about it?.

111
00:14:23,765 --> 00:14:29,186
No, that makes him sadder.

112
00:14:29,354 --> 00:14:32,058
'Jonah, is your dad home?

113
00:14:32,232 --> 00:14:36,893
- Is he busy?
- No, he's out on the deck.

114
00:14:37,070 --> 00:14:40,236
Can't you ask him to talk to me?

115
00:14:40,406 --> 00:14:46,279
- Wretched woman! Hang up, Jonah!
- No, he'd kill me.

116
00:14:46,454 --> 00:14:51,282
He won't be angry when he hears
how concerned you are about him.

117
00:14:51,459 --> 00:14:56,702
- Want to bet?
- If he yells, you lose a fan.

118
00:14:58,841 --> 00:15:04,547
Dad. there's someone
on the phone for you.

119
00:15:07,559 --> 00:15:10,096
His name is Sam.

120
00:15:10,270 --> 00:15:15,893
If you've just tuned in, tonight's
topic is wishes and dreams.

121
00:15:16,067 --> 00:15:19,566
We have a listener from Seattle.

122
00:15:19,737 --> 00:15:23,486
Sam, this is Dr. Fieldstone
on Network America.

123
00:15:23,658 --> 00:15:28,901
What are you selling?
Micro-hibachis or knives?

124
00:15:29,080 --> 00:15:34,240
Neither. I want to help.
Your son asked me for advice.

125
00:15:34,419 --> 00:15:39,544
- He wants to find you a new wife.
- Who is this?

126
00:15:39,716 --> 00:15:45,339
Dr. Fieldstone of Network America.
You are on the air.

127
00:15:45,513 --> 00:15:49,842
- You called a radio station?
- Sam, are you there?

128
00:15:50,018 --> 00:15:55,854
- Yes.
- You mourn your wife's death.

129
00:15:56,024 --> 00:15:59,523
Your son is worried about you.

130
00:15:59,694 --> 00:16:04,273
Get out here.
I won't go through this alone.

131
00:16:04,449 --> 00:16:08,612
It's hard for him
to talk to you about this.

132
00:16:08,786 --> 00:16:13,532
If we talk about it,
maybe 'Jonah will feel better.

133
00:16:13,708 --> 00:16:18,951
- Talk to her. She's a doctor.
- Her first name could be Doctor.

134
00:16:19,130 --> 00:16:26,129
- Please.
- Sam, it's his Christmas wish.

135
00:16:26,304 --> 00:16:29,009
- Okay.
- Good.

136
00:16:29,182 --> 00:16:34,425
I know this is difficult.
When did your wife die?

137
00:16:35,480 --> 00:16:41,020
- About a year and a half ago.
- Have you had any relationships?

138
00:16:41,861 --> 00:16:46,238
- No.
- Why not?.

139
00:16:48,159 --> 00:16:52,073
- Marcia ... or Dr. Fieldstone?
- Dr. Marcia.

140
00:16:52,247 --> 00:16:58,415
- I don't mean to be rude ...
- I don't want to pry ...

141
00:16:58,586 --> 00:17:05,964
- Sure you do.
- Go on, Sam. I'm listening.

142
00:17:06,135 --> 00:17:11,378
We had a pretty tough time at first.

143
00:17:11,558 --> 00:17:15,851
But we're dealing with it.

144
00:17:16,020 --> 00:17:22,224
Jonah and I will get along fine,
as soon as I break his radio.

145
00:17:23,736 --> 00:17:26,940
I'm sure you're a wonderful father.

146
00:17:27,115 --> 00:17:31,029
- You can tell a lot from a voice.
- Yes, you can.

147
00:17:31,202 --> 00:17:35,449
But 'Jonah still feels
that you're under a cloud.

148
00:17:35,623 --> 00:17:40,997
- Are you sleeping at night?.
- He doesn't sleep at all.

149
00:17:41,170 --> 00:17:45,417
- How do you know that?
- I live here. Dad.

150
00:17:47,385 --> 00:17:50,968
Look. it's Christmas.

151
00:17:54,809 --> 00:17:58,510
Maggie ... my wife.

152
00:17:58,688 --> 00:18:01,689
She really did it ...

153
00:18:01,858 --> 00:18:06,520
She loved ...
She made everything beautiful.

154
00:18:08,656 --> 00:18:12,488
It's tough this time of year.

155
00:18:12,660 --> 00:18:19,908
- Every kid needs a mother.
- Maybe you need someone, too.

156
00:18:22,128 --> 00:18:26,837
- Yes.
- We'll resume after these messages.

157
00:18:27,008 --> 00:18:33,545
Sam and 'Jonah, don't go away.
I'm talking to Sleepless in Seattle.

158
00:18:33,723 --> 00:18:37,721
We'll be back
with listener response.

159
00:18:37,894 --> 00:18:44,347
- What's that?
- People call in and dump on you.

160
00:18:44,525 --> 00:18:48,393
This is really fun. And helpful.

161
00:18:54,452 --> 00:19:00,241
- I bet he's tall with a cute butt.
- I bet he hasn't bathed in weeks.

162
00:19:00,416 --> 00:19:03,453
- Yes?
- Tea, with the bag out.

163
00:19:03,628 --> 00:19:10,793
- Maybe I'll just go up to Seattle.
- Don't open his refrigerator.

164
00:19:10,969 --> 00:19:16,390
Men don't cover food, and they
leave it in there till it walks out.

165
00:19:16,558 --> 00:19:21,896
I wouldn't kick him out of bed
for eating crackers. 65 cents.

166
00:19:22,063 --> 00:19:28,777
We'll take a call before we talk to
Sleepless. Go ahead, Tennessee.

167
00:19:28,987 --> 00:19:33,613
I'd like to have his address.

168
00:19:33,783 --> 00:19:37,650
Honey, get in line.

169
00:19:38,830 --> 00:19:44,120
- If I could ask you a question ...
- Go ahead.

170
00:19:44,294 --> 00:19:48,422
People who truly loved
are likely to love again.

171
00:19:48,590 --> 00:19:54,924
Sam, could you love anybody
as much as you loved your wife?

172
00:19:56,055 --> 00:20:00,349
Well, that's hard to imagine.

173
00:20:00,518 --> 00:20:03,638
What are you going to do?

174
00:20:03,813 --> 00:20:11,026
Get out of bed every morning
and breathe in and out all day.

175
00:20:11,195 --> 00:20:19,369
And after a while I won't have to
remind myself to do it.

176
00:20:21,623 --> 00:20:29,417
And then after a while I won't
remember how perfect things were.

177
00:20:29,631 --> 00:20:33,878
Why was your wife so special?

178
00:20:34,052 --> 00:20:37,503
Howling is your program?

179
00:20:40,016 --> 00:20:44,429
It was a million little things.

180
00:20:44,604 --> 00:20:49,266
When you added them up, it meant
we were meant for each other.

181
00:20:49,442 --> 00:20:53,819
I knew it
the very first time I touched her.

182
00:20:53,988 --> 00:20:59,908
It was like coming home,
only to no home I'd ever known.

183
00:21:00,078 --> 00:21:03,363
I was just taking her hand -

184
00:21:03,539 --> 00:21:08,166
- to help her out of a car.
And I knew it.

185
00:21:09,462 --> 00:21:14,005
- It was ... Like magic.
- Magic.

186
00:21:14,801 --> 00:21:20,506
It's time to wrap it up.
I'm Dr. Marcia Fieldstone.

187
00:21:20,682 --> 00:21:25,011
To all my listeners,
a magical and Merry Christmas.

188
00:21:25,186 --> 00:21:32,434
And Sleepless in Seattle,
call and tell us how it's going.

189
00:21:32,610 --> 00:21:35,647
You can count on it.

190
00:22:23,828 --> 00:22:28,704
He sells the best soup ever and
he is the meanest man in America.

191
00:22:28,875 --> 00:22:33,537
- I feel strongly about this.
- Do it.

192
00:22:33,713 --> 00:22:36,286
New Year's Eve. I won't write it.

193
00:22:36,466 --> 00:22:40,713
Listen: "Phone service was
tied up Christmas Eve -

194
00:22:40,887 --> 00:22:45,216
- when a kid called the radio
and said his dad needs a new wife."

195
00:22:45,391 --> 00:22:49,092
2.000 women wanted his number.

196
00:22:49,270 --> 00:22:52,473
I heard it. This kid calls up, -

197
00:22:52,649 --> 00:22:58,734
- and the shrink forces
the father to talk about it.

198
00:22:58,905 --> 00:23:02,025
Suddenly he starts talking -

199
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:08,618
- about how he fell in love with her
like these cows in Michigan.

200
00:23:08,790 --> 00:23:14,294
The cows that got zapped by stray
voltage. Maybe it was Wisconsin.

201
00:23:14,462 --> 00:23:20,915
Anyway, I was listening to him,
and suddenly I was crying.

202
00:23:21,094 --> 00:23:24,260
Like when I see the ad -

203
00:23:24,430 --> 00:23:29,388
- where the daughter gives her mum
the refrigerator with a red bow.

204
00:23:29,561 --> 00:23:35,184
- Or the to kids at the party ...
- Making an album for Grandfather!

205
00:23:35,358 --> 00:23:38,941
That kills me!

206
00:23:39,112 --> 00:23:42,812
Write about it. Whatever it is.

207
00:23:42,991 --> 00:23:48,780
2,000 women calling for a husband?
Women are desperate for love.

208
00:23:48,955 --> 00:23:54,198
- Especially over a certain age.
- It's hard to get married over 40.

209
00:23:54,377 --> 00:23:59,253
- That statistic is not true.
- But it feels true.

210
00:23:59,424 --> 00:24:04,845
- It's true.
- A new book proves it isn't true.

211
00:24:05,013 --> 00:24:09,342
- Did you read that book?
- Did anybody read that book?

212
00:24:09,517 --> 00:24:12,720
Are you done? Where were we?

213
00:24:12,896 --> 00:24:19,812
If someone's a widower, why is he
widowed and not widowered?

214
00:24:21,613 --> 00:24:24,364
Just wondering.

215
00:24:24,532 --> 00:24:28,945
What was that about up there?
What's with you?

216
00:24:29,120 --> 00:24:36,914
- Nothing.
- There's something. Tell me.

217
00:24:37,086 --> 00:24:41,166
- Sleepless in Seattle?
- That's what she called him.

218
00:24:41,341 --> 00:24:45,635
Now 2.000 women want his number.
He could be a crack head. -

219
00:24:45,803 --> 00:24:53,384
- a transvestite, a junkie,
or really sick, like my Rick.

220
00:24:54,729 --> 00:24:58,145
Actually, he sounded nice.

221
00:24:59,317 --> 00:25:04,394
Really?
Now we're getting down to it.

222
00:25:04,572 --> 00:25:09,863
I'm madly in love with Walter. He
did a crazy thing the other night.

223
00:25:11,913 --> 00:25:17,749
It was so funny.
What was that?

224
00:25:27,345 --> 00:25:32,422
I've got to go to Boston
for the convention.

225
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:36,598
And I have to visit Winston-Hughes.

226
00:25:37,188 --> 00:25:41,435
Why don't we meet in New York
