00:55:58,051 --> 00:56:01,135
- No.
- Is that the reason you're calling?

456
00:56:01,304 --> 00:56:06,643
We can get cheap tickets
from Jessica's parents.

457
00:56:06,809 --> 00:56:11,056
We'll talk about it later.

458
00:56:11,231 --> 00:56:16,391
This conversation has lasted
too long. Go to bed.

459
00:56:22,033 --> 00:56:26,410
- Everything all right?
- Yes. Do you have kids?

460
00:56:26,579 --> 00:56:29,782
You want mine?

461
00:56:30,667 --> 00:56:34,914
I'll have an Absolut straight up.

462
00:56:51,563 --> 00:56:55,228
Put that down. Stop it!

463
00:56:55,400 --> 00:56:59,528
- There she is.
- Why is she bringing groceries?

464
00:56:59,696 --> 00:57:04,773
- She's going to cook for us.
- Hi. Sam.

465
00:57:04,951 --> 00:57:08,996
Let me guess. You must be Jonah.

466
00:57:11,874 --> 00:57:16,335
This is it? The car is this way.

467
00:57:16,504 --> 00:57:23,420
She's on her sixth painter. And now
she wants the fireplace rebricked.

468
00:57:23,595 --> 00:57:30,131
- I know her. I could call her.
- I'll just hit her with a brick.

469
00:57:32,645 --> 00:57:35,682
That's so funny. You're so funny.

470
00:57:35,857 --> 00:57:41,895
When she wants something done
she says: "You know best."

471
00:57:42,071 --> 00:57:47,314
"But couldn't we flip the house
so the back is in front?"

472
00:57:47,493 --> 00:57:53,579
"Put the front on a hinge so I can
get in with a garage door opener."

473
00:57:53,750 --> 00:58:00,037
- "Yes, we can. We'll just ..."
- "Move the cabinets."

474
00:58:07,222 --> 00:58:10,970
Jonah, bring some of that stuff.

475
00:58:11,142 --> 00:58:14,178
Do you like baseball?

476
00:58:14,354 --> 00:58:19,265
Yes. In fact my firm has box seats
to the Mariners. Let's go some day.

477
00:58:20,985 --> 00:58:25,813
What about camping?
Do you like that?

478
00:58:25,990 --> 00:58:28,777
I went camping once.

479
00:58:28,952 --> 00:58:34,705
- We should go camping more often.
- You're right. Time for bed.

480
00:58:34,874 --> 00:58:39,453
- It's only 10:00.
- That's right. Time for bed.

481
00:58:39,629 --> 00:58:42,630
Goodnight.

482
00:58:44,259 --> 00:58:48,256
Thank Victoria for the nice dinner.

483
00:58:48,429 --> 00:58:53,506
Thanks for dinner. I never saw
anybody cook potatoes that way.

484
00:58:53,685 --> 00:58:59,438
I'm glad you liked it.
Goodnight, Jonah.

485
00:59:00,733 --> 00:59:06,688
We don't see a lot of potatoes here.
We're rice men.

486
01:00:00,210 --> 01:00:03,460
I'm sorry, Walter. I'm sorry.

487
01:00:08,176 --> 01:00:10,797
Turn on your radio.

488
01:00:10,970 --> 01:00:15,965
The kid is on. You've got me
listening to this garbage!

489
01:00:16,893 --> 01:00:23,975
Becky's having trouble with Rick.
Becky, I'll call you back.

490
01:00:26,819 --> 01:00:31,316
I'm sorry, Walter.
Are you bleeding?

491
01:00:50,510 --> 01:00:53,677
He's kissing her right now!

492
01:00:53,846 --> 01:00:57,630
Are you spying on your father?.

493
01:00:57,809 --> 01:01:02,850
- Who is he kissing?
- I have to make them stop.

494
01:01:03,022 --> 01:01:07,150
- How will I explain this to Walter?
- She made dinner.

495
01:01:07,318 --> 01:01:10,521
She brought food for a whole year!

496
01:01:10,697 --> 01:01:15,193
It's good that your father's dating.
It's just hard on you.

497
01:01:15,368 --> 01:01:19,745
You think you want it,
but when it happens, it scares you.

498
01:01:19,914 --> 01:01:25,371
Shouldn't your father decide
whether someone is right for him?

499
01:01:25,545 --> 01:01:27,834
He's not sane enough.

500
01:01:28,006 --> 01:01:33,878
He's kissing her on the lips.
My dad's been captured by a 'ho!

501
01:01:34,053 --> 01:01:38,762
Calm down. Tomorrow,
when you're having breakfast, -

502
01:01:38,933 --> 01:01:44,806
- tell him how you feel.
Don't keep it inside.

503
01:01:49,360 --> 01:01:53,939
Miss Scarlett. In the broom closet.
With the radio.

504
01:01:54,115 --> 01:01:59,655
Walter, you scared me.
Don't ever do that again.

505
01:02:02,540 --> 01:02:07,286
- I saw a black widow.
- You scared me and Victoria.

506
01:02:07,462 --> 01:02:12,420
- It was right there.
- Next time I want you to say:

507
01:02:12,592 --> 01:02:16,886
"Dad, I see a poisonous insect."

508
01:02:17,055 --> 01:02:20,506
And I'll deal with it. Don't scream.

509
01:02:20,683 --> 01:02:25,179
Becky thought Rick was on the radio.

510
01:02:25,355 --> 01:02:31,274
It turned out the guy lived
in Duluth. Where's Duluth?

511
01:02:31,444 --> 01:02:35,905
- That doesn't make any sense.
- I know. No sense at all.

512
01:02:36,074 --> 01:02:41,779
- Thank God my life is in place.
- Duluth? That's in North Dakota.

513
01:02:56,135 --> 01:03:01,047
- Great letter. Write to her.
- You think so?

514
01:03:01,224 --> 01:03:06,728
It's Y-O-H.
Your only hope.

515
01:03:18,449 --> 01:03:23,870
I thought I'd do a story
on those radio shows.

516
01:03:24,038 --> 01:03:28,665
- You'd have to go somewhere.
- Definitely.

517
01:03:47,562 --> 01:03:51,939
- Can't you do a phone interview?
- No.

518
01:03:52,108 --> 01:03:56,402
- I won't be in Chicago long.
- When you get back, I'll be gone.

519
01:03:56,571 --> 01:04:00,699
- Then I'll see you in New York.
- I'll get it ...

520
01:04:04,871 --> 01:04:09,948
This is Captain Browning.
We're cruising at 35,000 feet.

521
01:04:10,126 --> 01:04:15,583
The weather is clear
and we'll be in Seattle on schedule.

522
01:04:15,757 --> 01:04:23,633
- Don't you hate flying?
- Yes. and I've told a terrible lie.

523
01:04:23,806 --> 01:04:27,756
Is any lie a betrayal?

524
01:04:27,936 --> 01:04:32,265
I said flying.

525
01:04:37,445 --> 01:04:41,858
- Thanks for bringing me here.
- He likes the planes.

526
01:04:42,033 --> 01:04:48,830
Can I bring you back a souvenir?
Maybe one of these snow globes?

527
01:04:48,998 --> 01:04:53,826
Sure, I'd really like that.
Thank you so much.

528
01:04:55,255 --> 01:04:58,873
- He's eight.
- He's good at it.

529
01:04:59,050 --> 01:05:04,092
I've read an article about it.
Children are hideous at that age.

530
01:05:04,264 --> 01:05:11,227
Maybe when I come back, the to of
us ought to spend some time alone.

531
01:05:15,733 --> 01:05:18,853
Bye. Bye, Jonah.

532
01:05:24,117 --> 01:05:26,323
Jonah.

533
01:05:26,494 --> 01:05:29,993
Listen, you don't know Victoria.

534
01:05:30,164 --> 01:05:35,289
In fact she's a mystery to me, too.

535
01:05:35,461 --> 01:05:39,506
She tosses her hair a lot. Why?

536
01:05:39,674 --> 01:05:44,669
Is it a titch? Does she need
a haircut or a barrette?

537
01:05:46,306 --> 01:05:53,720
I'd like to understand these things.
And that's why I'm dating her.

538
01:05:53,897 --> 01:05:59,271
Just dating. I'm not living
with her. I'm not marrying her.

539
01:05:59,444 --> 01:06:02,979
Can you appreciate the difference?

540
01:06:03,156 --> 01:06:07,782
That's what single people do.
They see how other people fit.

541
01:06:07,952 --> 01:06:14,536
Everyone's an adjustment. There's
no such thing as a perfect ...

542
01:06:29,891 --> 01:06:33,474
Come on.

543
01:06:34,020 --> 01:06:40,604
Dad, Jessica says
you knew Annie in another life.

544
01:06:40,777 --> 01:06:45,569
The one who wrote us. But you
never got together in that life.

545
01:06:45,740 --> 01:06:51,659
Your hearts will be a complete
puzzle once you're together.

546
01:06:51,829 --> 01:06:58,662
I know that because I'm young and
pure, in touch with cosmic forces.

547
01:06:58,836 --> 01:07:04,376
Who told you that? I sure hope
you're not marrying Jessica.

548
01:09:48,047 --> 01:09:52,875
- I watched them play at the beach.
- Did you talk to him?

549
01:09:53,052 --> 01:09:56,635
Couldn't do it.

550
01:09:56,806 --> 01:10:02,512
- How did I get here?
- You lied and got on a plane.

551
01:10:03,771 --> 01:10:11,103
- I'm going to talk to him tomorrow.
- Okay. Good. Goodbye.

552
01:10:11,279 --> 01:10:14,695
Beck ...

553
01:10:15,366 --> 01:10:21,202
- Is this crazy?
- No, that's the weirdest part

554
01:10:21,372 --> 01:10:27,493
- Thank you. I love you.
- I love you, too.

555
01:11:29,899 --> 01:11:34,193
It's good to see you. Where's Greg?

556
01:11:57,093 --> 01:12:01,173
Hello.

557
01:12:07,854 --> 01:12:12,231
- Then what?
- I left, obviously.

558
01:12:12,400 --> 01:12:18,154
- You were in the street?
- It was like walking around naked.

559
01:12:18,323 --> 01:12:23,993
- I love that dream.
- This was more humiliating.

560
01:12:24,162 --> 01:12:28,206
But he saw you.
You were face to face.

561
01:12:28,374 --> 01:12:35,207
He said hello.
And all I could say was hello.

562
01:12:36,132 --> 01:12:41,719
- All I could say was hello.
- It's a sign.

563
01:12:41,888 --> 01:12:47,013
It's a sign that I've watched
this movie too many times.

564
01:12:47,185 --> 01:12:53,804
From the minute I heard that program
I've been a complete jerk.

565
01:12:53,983 --> 01:12:57,851
- You're not a jerk.
- Thank you. An idiot!

566
01:12:58,029 --> 01:13:03,783
- You don't know who she was.
- I have a picture of her.

567
01:13:03,952 --> 01:13:10,286
The detective sent it to me.
See. that's what she looks like.

568
01:13:11,167 --> 01:13:16,292
- It's her back.
- It's her and he's crazy about her.

569
01:13:16,464 --> 01:13:21,375
What's this?
It's from Seattle.

570
01:13:28,434 --> 01:13:31,139
Becky.

571
01:13:32,230 --> 01:13:35,681
So I mailed your letter ...

572
01:13:36,401 --> 01:13:42,439
"Dear Annie. Thanks for your letter.
You sound neat."

573
01:13:45,743 --> 01:13:50,904
"We're excited about meeting you
in New York, and seeing if we're ...

574
01:13:51,082 --> 01:13:55,543
... M-F-E-O."

575
01:13:55,712 --> 01:13:59,923
"See you soon.
Sleepless in Seattle."

576
01:14:00,091 --> 01:14:04,136
M-F-E-O?

577
01:14:05,930 --> 01:14:09,548
Made for each other.

578
01:14:09,726 --> 01:14:12,892
It's cute. Like a little clue.

579
01:14:17,483 --> 01:14:20,852
So he can't write. Big deal.

580
01:14:21,029 --> 01:14:26,699
Verbal ability is overrated in guys.
Our need for it leads to trouble.

581
01:14:26,868 --> 01:14:31,909
- I'm going to run back to Walter.
- And the letter?

582
01:14:32,081 --> 01:14:36,874
It was written before I went
out there. Before the 'ho.

583
01:14:39,505 --> 01:14:46,504
But she didn't look like a 'ho.
She looked like one of our friends.

584
01:14:50,225 --> 01:14:56,014
- You saw her in the airport, too?
- It was like I knew her.

585
01:14:56,189 --> 01:15:01,610
- Like a deja-vu?
- It was very deja-vu-ish.

586
01:15:01,778 --> 01:15:07,448
- At least you're seeing people.
- Well, only one ...

587
01:15:07,617 --> 01:15:11,745
- Victoria.
- You don't like her?

588
01:15:11,913 --> 01:15:17,204
- She laughs like a hyena.
- Is this true?

589
01:15:17,377 --> 01:15:21,540
Sort of. Tell them what you did.

590
01:15:21,714 --> 01:15:24,964
Tell them about the radio show.

591
01:15:25,134 --> 01:15:28,883
Christmas Eve he calls a radio show.

592
01:15:29,055 --> 01:15:35,936
- And tells them I need a new wife.
- That's so sweet.

593
01:15:36,104 --> 01:15:40,184
Now he's obsessed with
a woman who wrote me.

594
01:15:40,358 --> 01:15:45,565
She wants to meet me on top of
Empire State on Valentines Day.

595
01:15:45,738 --> 01:15:51,362
It's like that movie.
"An Affair to Remember".

596
01:15:51,536 --> 01:15:56,613
Cary Grant and Deborah Kerr.
Is that "car" or "cur"?

597
01:15:59,961 --> 01:16:05,715
They were to meet at the Empire
State, but she got hit by a taxi.

598
01:16:05,884 --> 01:16:10,759
He waited and waited.
And it was raining.

599
01:16:10,930 --> 01:16:17,384
Then she's too proud
to tell him that she's ...

600
01:16:19,772 --> 01:16:25,645
... crippled. And he's too proud
to find out why she doesn't come.

601
01:16:25,820 --> 01:16:29,688
But he comes to see her anyway.

602
01:16:29,866 --> 01:16:34,575
It's amazing when he visits her.

603
01:16:34,746 --> 01:16:39,455
He doesn't notice that she
doesn't get up to say hello.

604
01:16:39,626 --> 01:16:42,876
And he's very bitter.

605
01:16:43,046 --> 01:16:47,921
You think he's going to walk out
and never know why.

606
01:16:48,092 --> 01:16:56,302
She's just lying there with
a blanket over her shriveled legs.

607
01:16:58,394 --> 01:17:01,598
- Are you all right?
- She's fine.

608
01:17:01,773 --> 01:17:08,226
The he says, "I saw the painting,"
and goes into the bedroom.

609
01:17:08,404 --> 01:17:12,354
And he comes out and looks at her.

610
01:17:12,533 --> 01:17:17,030
And they just know
and hug and it's so ...

611
01:17:17,205 --> 01:17:20,823
- That's a chick's movie.
- I'd say so.

612
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:26,873
- Who'd write a guy from the radio?
- I got hundreds of letters.

613
01:17:27,048 --> 01:17:31,757
- Desperate women.
- Is wanting a nice guy desperate?

614
01:17:31,928 --> 01:17:37,384
It's easier to be killed
by terrorists than to marry over 40.

615
01:17:37,559 --> 01:17:41,971
- That is not true!
- Right, honey.

616
01:17:42,146 --> 01:17:47,603
I don't want a mail-order bride.
Just someone who can converse -

617
01:17:47,777 --> 01:17:53,613
- without falling into
weepy tears over an old movie.

618
01:17:53,783 --> 01:17:59,821
I cried over "The Dirty Dozen".
Jim Brown throwing the grenades.

619
01:17:59,998 --> 01:18:05,621
Richard Jaeckel and Lee Marvin
on top of a tank dressed like nazis.

620
01:18:07,338 --> 01:18:14,337
Trini Lopez ... breaks his neck
when they're parachuting.

621
01:18:14,512 --> 01:18:19,340
Richard Jaeckel had on a shiny
helmet. because he was an MP.

622
01:18:19,517 --> 01:18:24,263
Please. no more.
God. I love that movie.

623
01:18:32,655 --> 01:18:37,364
- This is the best movie I ever saw.
- What's so great about it?

624
01:18:37,535 --> 01:18:42,197
- You have to find her.
- How much would it cost to go?

625
01:18:42,373 --> 01:18:47,035
Nobody knows.
It changes practically every day.

626
01:18:47,212 --> 01:18:50,497
- How much money do you have?
- 80 dollars.

627
01:18:50,673 --> 01:18:56,676
- I have 42. That'll cover cabs.
- How would I get there?

628
01:18:56,846 --> 01:19:02,600
I have to drop these tickets off.
Can you keep an eye on things?

629
01:19:12,946 --> 01:19:16,231
- Window seat or aisle?
- Window.

630
01:19:16,407 --> 01:19:21,200
You want a fruit plate? I'd rather
die than eat airplane food.

631
01:19:21,371 --> 01:19:25,665
I'll write you're 12.
That way you can fly unaccompanied.

632
01:19:25,833 --> 01:19:32,417
- Who'd believe I'm 12?
- They'll believe the computer.

633
01:19:32,590 --> 01:19:38,047
I'll say you're short for your age,
but that they shouldn't mention it.

634
01:19:38,221 --> 01:19:40,463
Great idea!

635
01:20:00,743 --> 01:20:04,611
- You'll miss the train.
- No I won't.

636
01:20:04,789 --> 01:20:10,294
I'm so happy, Becky.
This is right. It's real.

637
01:20:10,461 --> 01:20:15,622
The other things happen in movies.

638
01:20:15,800 --> 01:20:19,845
Don't tell anyone what I did.
I'd die -

639
01:20:20,013 --> 01:20:26,431
- if anyone knew I did anything
like that. You promise?

640
01:20:26,603 --> 01:20:30,850
Sleepless in Seattle is history.

641
01:21:03,264 --> 01:21:06,467
- Go ahead.
- No, you go.

642
01:21:06,643 --> 01:21:10,890
I was going to say
that since Christmas -

643
01:21:11,064 --> 01:21:15,013
- you've been kind of distracted.

644
01:21:15,193 --> 01:21:21,480
But now it feels as if you're coming
back from wherever you were.

645
01:21:21,658 --> 01:21:24,943
I am.

646
01:21:25,119 --> 01:21:31,158
I was just ...
I think I got nervous.

647
01:21:31,876 --> 01:21:38,757
But that's normal, right?
Don't you ever feel nervous ...

648
01:21:39,926 --> 01:21:44,884
- About what?
- Forever.

649
01:21:45,557 --> 01:21:48,723
No.

650
01:21:50,436 --> 01:21:55,182
Well ... I did.

651
01:21:55,358 --> 01:22:00,649
And I think I thought
it was too perfect.

652
01:22:00,822 --> 01:22:06,527
I was afraid we'd be to rights
making a wrong.

653
01:22:06,703 --> 01:22:13,500
You know. it was like kismet.
but not, if you see what I mean.

654
01:22:13,668 --> 01:22:18,663
You have to grow up and forget
the adolescent fantasies about -

655
01:22:18,840 --> 01:22:23,383
- how exciting life will be.
I'm sorry, but I love this pattern.

656
01:22:23,553 --> 01:22:28,298
You couldn't. This is just
like my grandmother's china.

657
01:22:28,474 --> 01:22:32,971
- How many place settings?
- Ten.

658
01:22:35,064 --> 01:22:41,731
Exactly. Eight is too few,
twelve is too many.

659
01:23:04,636 --> 01:23:09,179
- Walter ...
- It was my mother's.

660
01:23:10,141 --> 01:23:15,895
I had them size it down.
She had really fat fingers.

661
01:23:18,358 --> 01:23:22,605
It's so beautiful.
It's exactly what I'd pick -

662
01:23:22,779 --> 01:23:28,021
- if I had every ring
in the world to choose from.

663
01:23:29,035 --> 01:23:33,827
Some people want a relationship
to be full of surprises, -

664
01:23:33,998 --> 01:23:38,245
- but I'm not one of them.

665
01:23:38,878 --> 01:23:43,457
Surprises are highly overrated.

666
01:23:44,384 --> 01:23:44,425
I'll only be gone one night.
Clarise will be here ...

667
01:23:44,425 --> 01:23:49,301
I'll only be gone one night.
Clarise will be here ...

668
01:23:49,472 --> 01:23:53,422
You can watch scary movies.

669
01:23:53,601 --> 01:23:58,512
- Are you going with her?
- I'm going with Victoria.

670
01:24:00,858 --> 01:24:04,477
Don't try anything tricky.

671
01:24:06,698 --> 01:24:13,234
Don't roll in poison ivy or
do anything so you need stitches.

672
01:24:13,413 --> 01:24:20,246
If your finger falls off, it stays
off. I won't take you to hospital.

673
01:24:21,170 --> 01:24:25,334
- Is this about that woman?
- Annie.

674
01:24:28,887 --> 01:24:33,216
- I don't care what you do!
- I'll tell you what I'm doing.

675
01:24:33,391 --> 01:24:39,394
I'm getting laid. I'm the only man
in the 90's who's getting laid.

676
01:24:39,564 --> 01:24:45,151
And I haven't been laid that much.
Six or seven girls at college.

677
01:24:45,320 --> 01:24:49,317
How long have you been there?
What did you hear me say?

678
01:24:49,490 --> 01:24:54,947
-"Six-seven girls at college."
- Seven ... Eight! Mary Kelly.

679
01:24:55,121 --> 01:24:59,249
This is the one I like.

680
01:24:59,417 --> 01:25:04,293
Jonah, you won't like any woman,
because it isn't your mother.

681
01:25:04,464 --> 01:25:09,754
- What's wrong with Annie?
- Jonah, shut up.

682
01:25:09,928 --> 01:25:15,930
Shut up? Mum never told me
to shut up or yelled at me.

683
01:25:16,100 --> 01:25:19,018
This conversation is over!

684
01:25:19,187 --> 01:25:25,770
This woman could be a sick lunatic.
Didn't you see "Fatal Attraction"?

685
01:25:25,944 --> 01:25:31,733
- You wouldn't let me.
- It scared every man in America.

686
01:25:33,743 --> 01:25:37,871
I'm not leaving till you say yes.

687
01:25:41,834 --> 01:25:44,076
I hate you!

688
01:25:44,254 --> 01:25:48,203
Good, then you can tell Oprah
how your dad ruined your life -

689
01:25:48,383 --> 01:25:52,546
- by going of for a weekend
special at the Holiday Inn!

690
01:26:07,068 --> 01:26:12,228
Jonah. Clarise is here
and I've got to go.

691
01:26:21,165 --> 01:26:27,002
Jonah. Listen.
I've got to go ...

692
01:26:54,240 --> 01:27:00,243
Jessica. tell us where he is.
Jonah's dad is very upset.

693
01:27:00,413 --> 01:27:05,834
Jessica, this is your father.
Tell us where he is.

694
01:27:07,712 --> 01:27:11,046
- N-Y.
- That means "no way".

695
01:27:11,216 --> 01:27:14,086
That's N-W!

696
01:27:14,260 --> 01:27:19,468
- He's on his way to New York.
- How?

697
01:27:19,641 --> 01:27:22,677
United. 597.

698
01:27:22,852 --> 01:27:26,517
- When does it leave?
- 7:30.

699
01:27:32,445 --> 01:27:36,906
Here's a pin for flying with us.

700
01:27:37,075 --> 01:27:40,859
- Can I take this for you?
- No.

701
01:27:55,218 --> 01:27:59,216
- Where to. kid?
- Empire State Building.

702
01:27:59,389 --> 01:28:03,718
- Empire State Building.
- Don't stop so close to the curb.

703
01:28:05,728 --> 01:28:10,936
There it is. What are you going
to do up there? Spit off the top?

704
01:28:11,109 --> 01:28:14,312
No, I'm meeting my new mother.

705
01:28:34,465 --> 01:28:40,420
- I'm Jonah. Are you Annie?
- No, I'm Cynthia.

706
01:28:46,769 --> 01:28:50,981
Excuse me, are you Annie?

707
01:29:27,810 --> 01:29:30,930
Great table. Thanks.

708
01:29:32,148 --> 01:29:35,019
Is something wrong?

709
01:29:35,193 --> 01:29:39,237
- Can I get you a drink?
- Champagne?

710
01:29:39,405 --> 01:29:41,979
Fine.

711
01:29:42,158 --> 01:29:46,370
We'll have a bottle of Dom DeLuise.

712
01:29:48,748 --> 01:29:53,743
- Just kidding.
- He meant Dom Perignon.

713
01:29:56,005 --> 01:29:59,125
Beautiful view.

714
01:29:59,300 --> 01:30:03,843
Walter ...
There's something I must tell you.

715
01:30:18,486 --> 01:30:21,772
Sorry, an emergency.

716
01:30:21,948 --> 01:30:26,076
Money, money, money, see?

717
01:31:41,486 --> 01:31:46,444
So he could be on top of
the Empire State Building now?

718
01:31:46,616 --> 01:31:52,322
No. I guess he could be ... No.

719
01:31:52,956 --> 01:31:58,958
It's not him. Walter. It's me.
I can't do this.

720
01:32:00,755 --> 01:32:07,552
Annie, I love you.
But let's leave that out of this.

721
01:32:08,513 --> 01:32:15,310
I don't want to be someone that you
or anybody else settles for.

722
01:32:17,313 --> 01:32:22,770
Marriage is hard enough
without such low expectations.

723
01:32:22,944 --> 01:32:27,487
- Isn't it?
- Walter, I don't deserve you.

724
01:32:28,324 --> 01:32:32,192
No, I wouldn't put it that way.

725
01:32:32,370 --> 01:32:36,415
But ... okay.

726
01:32:50,847 --> 01:32:56,719
- You okay?
- Yeah.

727
01:33:00,064 --> 01:33:03,314
- What?
- Look.

728
01:33:10,825 --> 01:33:14,870
- It's a sign.
- Who needed a sign?

729
01:33:15,038 --> 01:33:18,952
Walter, I have to go.

730
01:33:32,013 --> 01:33:35,180
Jonah!

731
01:33:37,810 --> 01:33:40,847
Dad!

732
01:33:54,035 --> 01:33:58,246
What if something happened to you?
What if I couldn't get to you?

733
01:33:58,414 --> 01:34:02,744
I'm sorry.

734
01:34:03,378 --> 01:34:08,799
What would I have done?
You're my family. You're all I have.

735
01:34:08,967 --> 01:34:11,588
I thought she'd be here.

736
01:34:11,761 --> 01:34:16,921
We're doing okay, right?
So far, have I done anything stupid?

737
01:34:17,100 --> 01:34:22,094
- Have I screwed it up for us?
- No.

738
01:35:13,323 --> 01:35:17,901
- Observation deck?
- Sorry, it's too late.

739
01:35:18,077 --> 01:35:23,617
- Please. I need to get up there.
- We're closing up.

740
01:35:28,379 --> 01:35:34,382
Can I just take a look?
I'm supposed to meet someone.

741
01:35:34,552 --> 01:35:39,547
He's probably not there, but if
I don't look, I'll always wonder.

742
01:35:39,724 --> 01:35:43,936
- Cary Grant, right?
- You know that movie?

743
01:35:44,103 --> 01:35:48,053
It's one of my wife's favourites.

744
01:35:54,989 --> 01:35:59,568
Maybe when we get home
we'll get a dog.

745
01:35:59,744 --> 01:36:05,533
- Wouldn't you like to have a dog?
- Sure.

746
01:36:17,428 --> 01:36:21,722
I'm sorry, ma'am. Empty.

747
01:36:22,642 --> 01:36:28,063
- Can I take a minute?
- Go ahead.

748
01:37:40,970 --> 01:37:44,838
I left it by the telescopes.

749
01:38:09,958 --> 01:38:15,628
It's you.
I saw you in the street.

750
01:38:15,797 --> 01:38:20,126
- Are you Annie?
- Yes.

751
01:38:22,929 --> 01:38:26,464
You're Annie?

752
01:38:27,475 --> 01:38:31,639
- This must be yours.
- I'm Jonah.

753
01:38:31,813 --> 01:38:36,724
- This is my dad. His name is Sam.
- Hi. Jonah.

754
01:38:37,735 --> 01:38:40,606
Sam ...

755
01:38:43,783 --> 01:38:48,825
- And who's this?
- Howard.

756
01:39:04,262 --> 01:39:07,880
We'd better go.

757
01:39:13,104 --> 01:39:16,140
Shall we?

758
01:40:01,569 --> 01:40:05,899
Sam ... It's nice to meet you.

